@mitsuhiko right now waitress will write the data from the client to a file, once it has received all of the data from the remote client, it will then send it to a WSGI thread to be processed. It thus knows the Content-Length since it just wrote that data to disk (or if it is short enough, in memory).

waitress does not limit the amount of clients that can concurrently be connected and sending data to it, it limits the threads for the WSGI workers.

Since the WSGI is never "directly" connected with the remote endpoint, setting `wsgi.inpute_terminated` doesn't change anything.

