Found the solution. The permissions on the newly installed packages were incorrect:

    drwx--S---  8 root staff    4096 Feb 19 22:26 dateparser
    drwx--S---  2 root staff    4096 Feb 19 22:26 dateparser-0.7.0.dist-info
    drwx--S---  3 root staff    4096 Feb 19 22:26 dateparser_data
    drwxr-sr-x  5 root staff    4096 Feb 19 22:00 dateutil

If I fix them manually:

    # cd /usr/local/lib/python3.5/dist-packages 
    # find dateparser -type d -exec chmod 755 '{}' \;
    # find dateparser -type d -exec chmod 755 '{}' \;
    # find dateparser -type f -exec chmod 644 '{}' \;
    # find regex-2018.2.8.dist-info -type f -exec chmod 644 '{}' \;
    # find dateparser-0.7.0.dist-info -type f -exec chmod 644 '{}' \;
    # find dateparser_data -type f -exec chmod 644 '{}' \;
    # find dateparser-0.7.0.dist-info -type d -exec chmod 755 '{}' \;
    # find dateparser_data -type d -exec chmod 755 '{}' \;
    # find tzlocal -type d -exec chmod 755 '{}' \;
    $ find tzlocal-1.5.1.dist-info -type d -exec chmod 755 '{}' \;
    # find tzlocal -type f -exec chmod 644 '{}' \;
    
Now it works:

    $ python3 
    Python 3.5.2 (default, Nov 23 2017, 16:37:01) 
    [GCC 5.4.0 20160609] on linux
    Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
    >>> import dateparser

