Actually I think that this is quite simple.

1. Select the pixel(s) you are interested in from the raw colour stream (rs::stream::color)
2. Those pixels {x,y} will map directly to the synthetic depth stream rs::stream::depth_aligned_to_color
3. from there you can gather the depth and get a 3d point of the pixel from the depth intrinsics

consider the following code... where x1 and y1 are pixel coordinates from the color stream

```depth_intrinsics = dev->get_stream_intrinsics(rs::stream::depth);
const uint16_t * depth_image = (const uint16_t *)dev->get_frame_data(rs::stream::depth_aligned_to_color);
float scale = dev->get_depth_scale();
uint16_t p1_depth_value = depth_image[y1 * depth_intrinsics.width + x1];
float p1_depth_in_meters = p1_depth_value * scale;
rs::float2 p1_depth_pixel = {(float)x1, (float)y1};
rs::float3 p1_depth_point = depth_intrinsics.deproject(p1_depth_pixel, p1_depth_in_meters);
```
I believe this to give you a way to get a 3d point (p1_depth_point above) of a pixel coordinate from the color stream.
If you use the color stream to segment an object. You can get its 3D points via this means.

I haven't tested this extensively but it appears to work where I'm measuring the size of a test object.

